21. What is Exception Handling?
When an error occurs during program execution, Python normally stops the program.
Exception handling allows us to handle runtimeerrors and continue execution instead of crashing the program.
It improves the reliability and user-friendliness of an application.
num = int(input("Enter a number: "))
print(num) 
try:
    num = int(input("Enter a number: "))
    print(num)
except ValueError:
    print("Please enter a valid number")

try-the block which has the risky code
except - handles if any error occur in try block
finally - this block willl be executed anyways

compiletime vs runtime
compile time is when human-readable source code is translated into machine-readable code - compile errors During source code compilation.
while runtime is when that translated code is actively executed by a computer - runtime errors During program execution.
example:-
Think of compile time as baking a cake using a recipe (checking for missing ingredients), and 
runtime as eating the cake (finding out it tastes bad because you accidentally used salt instead of sugar).

22. What is try-except?
try contains code that may cause an error.
except contains code that runs if an error occurs.
Example
try:
    result = 10 / 0
except ZeroDivisionError:
    print("Cannot divide by zero")

23. What is finally?
The finally block always executes whether an exception occurs or not.
try:
    print(10 / 2)
except:
    print("Error")
finally:
    print("Execution completed")

Commonly used for:
Closing files - Closing database connections - Releasing resources

